If you're planning to get into Data Analytics, Data Science, AI, ML, or Data Engineering, learn:

1âƒ£Statistics & Mathematics â€“ Especially probability, linear algebra, calculus, and inferential stats

2âƒ£MS Excel, SQL, & Power BI â€“ For data manipulation, reporting, and dashboarding

3âƒ£Python â€“ With libraries like Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, Scikit-learn, etc.

4âƒ£Databases â€“ Relational (e.g., MySQL, PostgreSQL) and NoSQL (e.g., MongoDB)

5âƒ£Data Cleaning & Wrangling â€“ Using Python (Pandas) or SQL

6âƒ£Data Visualization â€“ Tools like Power BI, Tableau, or Python (Seaborn, Plotly)

7âƒ£Machine Learning â€“ Supervised, unsupervised, model evaluation, using Scikit-learn or TensorFlow

8âƒ£Big Data Tools â€“ Spark, Hadoop, or Databricks (especially for data engineering)

9âƒ£Cloud Platforms â€“ AWS, Azure, or GCP (focus on data-related services like S3, BigQuery, Redshift, etc.)

ğŸ”ŸVersion Control â€“ Git & GitHub for collaboration and tracking

1âƒ£1âƒ£APIs & Web Scraping â€“ Using Python (Requests, BeautifulSoup, Selenium)

1âƒ£2âƒ£Projects & Portfolio â€“ Build real-world projects and showcase them on GitHub and LinkedIn

1âƒ£3âƒ£Soft Skills â€“ Problem-solving, communication, storytelling with data

1âƒ£4âƒ£Domain Knowledge â€“ Understand the industry you're targeting (finance, healthcare, retail, etc.)

1âƒ£5âƒ£Job Readiness â€“ Resume building, mock interviews, case studies, and Kaggle competitions.
